<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">39007914</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2024</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>11</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>27</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1029-2292</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>42</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2024</Year><Month>Aug</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Growth factors (Chur, Switzerland)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Growth Factors</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Comparative effects of 8-week combined resistance exercise training and alternate-day calorie restriction on soluble epidermal growth factor receptor (sEGFR) and adipsin in obese men.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>111</StartPage><EndPage>119</EndPage><MedlinePgn>111-119</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/08977194.2024.2378889</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study investigated the combined effects of resistance exercise training (RET) and alternate-day calorie restriction (ADCR) on body composition, insulin resistance (IR), insulin resistance-related biomarkers (adipokine adipsin and hepatokine soluble EFGR), and weight loss in obese men. The findings revealed that RET&#x2009;+&#x2009;ADCR induced the greatest reductions in body weight, body fat percentage, and waist-to-hip ratio (WHR) compared to RET and ADCR alone (<i>p</i>&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.05). Additionally, RET&#x2009;+&#x2009;ADCR resulted in the most significant improvements in IR, as measured by HOMA-IR, and in circulating levels of adipsin and soluble EFGR (<i>p</i>&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;0.05). These findings suggest that combining RET and ADCR may be a more effective strategy for improving metabolic health, including body composition, IR, and metabolic tissues' functions, in obese men than either intervention alone.</AbstractText></Abstract><